<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Daniel M. Gitner, the 43-year-old defense lawyer who finally spoiled Preet Bhararaâs perfect record in hedge fund insider trading cases, is nothing if not thorough, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/09/daniel-gitner-the-defender-who-ended-prosecutors-winning-streak-in-trading-cases">Rachel Abrams writes in DealBook</a></b>. The insider trading trial of Mr. Gitnerâs client, the hedge fund trader Rengan Rajaratnam, which lasted about three weeks, required him and his team to sift through 2.5 terabytes of data, enough to store âWar and Peaceâ about 330,000 times. It was that thoroughness that helped Mr. Gitner rattle the office of Mr. Bharara, the United States attorney in Manhattan.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Tuesdayâs acquittal of Mr. Rajaratnam by a federal jury in Manhattan, after less than four hours of deliberation, was the <b>first defeat for the office</b> after 85 insider trading convictions and guilty pleas of hedge fund traders, analysts and others, including Mr. Rajaratnamâs older brother, Raj Rajatatnam, the founder of the Galleon Group hedge fund. âThere are a lot of great, great lawyers, and <b>nobody had won one of these cases in so long</b>,â Mr. Gitner, a former federal prosecutor, said on Wednesday. âJust showing that you can do it is what the message is.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Abrams writes: âIn the wake of the financial crisis, <b>public anger with Wall Street continues to simmer</b>, and it may be hard for jurors to sympathize much with those who have been accused of insider trading.â The publicâs lingering resentment, and Mr. Bhararaâs winning streak, was a cause for concern for Mr. Gitner, but in the end, he said the case showed that the publicâs negative opinion about those perceived to be Wall Street insiders will subside. â<b>Juries will truly weigh the evidence</b> and the lack of evidence,â he said.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> NEW LAWSUIT IN BATTLE OVER LIGHTSQUARED <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Philip A. Falconeâs hedge fund, Harbinger Capital Partners, filed a lawsuit on Tuesday against Dish Network, the satellite television company, and its chairman, Charles W. Ergen, accusing them of violating a federal racketeering law. The legal action is the latest chapter in a bitter fight between the two billionaires over LightSquared, the bankrupt wireless broadband company, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/09/falcones-harbinger-files-racketeering-lawsuit-against-ergen-over-lightsquared">DealBookâs William Alden writes</a></b>. Harbinger is seeking at least $1.5 billion in damages.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The lawsuit, running 99 pages, contends that Mr. Ergen and Dish <b>carried out a fraudulent scheme</b> to acquire LightSquaredâs wireless spectrum at bargain-basement prices. The suit echoes accusations aired last year in bankruptcy court, when Mr. Falcone asserted that Mr. Ergen colluded with a hedge fund to try to wrest control of LightSquared from Harbinger. Harbinger, the majority owner of LightSquared, now contends that Mr. Ergen <b>violated the Racketeering Influenced and Corrupt Organization Act</b> when he bought large amounts of LightSquaredâs debt while Dish was preparing a bid for LightSquaredâs assets.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> YOUNG BANKERS BEGIN WORK <span class="divider"> | </span></span> First-year junior bankers, most fresh out of college, do not get much of a summer vacation, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/09/for-young-bankers-the-job-starts-now">Sydney Ember writes in DealBook</a></b>. Instead, these young employees, known as analysts, are beginning training programs in New York geared to prepare them for work on Wall Street. The programs for new full-time bankers vary in length depending on bank and division. But most involve a mix of technical education â like learning how to use Excel to create financial models or calculate a payment on a bond â and networking activities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">New analysts often see the training programs as a bit of a break before the real work begins. â<b>Training is like a vacation</b>,â said one former JPMorgan investment banking analyst. âYouâre only working about eight or nine hours a day, so it really is your <b>last chance to drink and party and meet people</b>.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Weekly <b>jobless claims</b> are out at 8:30 a.m. The <b>wholesale trade</b> report comes out at 10 a.m. <b>Esther George</b>, the president of the Kansas City Fed, gives a speech on the economy and monetary policy at 1:15 p.m. in Shawnee, Okla. <b>Stanley Fischer</b>, the Fed vice chairman, gives a speech on financial sector reform at 4:30 p.m. in Cambridge, Mass.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>On the Hill</b>: The House <b>Committee on Financial Services</b> holds a hearing at 10 a.m. titled âLegislation to Reform the Federal Reserve on Its 100-year Anniversary.â The <b>Securities and Exchange Commission</b> holds an Investor Advisory Committee meeting at 10 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">DISPATCH FROM SUN VALLEY <span class="divider"> | </span></span> One of the perennial guessing games of the annual Allen &amp; Company conference in Sun Valley, Idaho, is who the big guest will be, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/09/this-years-special-guest-at-sun-valley-word-is-john-kerry/">Michael J. de la Merced writes in DealBook</a></b>. Word this year is that the special invitee is John F. Kerry, the secretary of state, who is expected to show up on Thursday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If Mr. Kerry attends, he will be the <b>latest government official to join the media and technology moguls</b> gathered at the conference. Mario Monti, Italyâs prime minister at the time, and Lee Hsien Loong, the prime minister of Singapore, have attended the conference in the past. A number of government officials are also on the official invite list, including <b>former Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg</b> of New York City, who strolled into the conference on Tuesday morning.</p>
</div>
